orcerers -- tCHAPTER 13 Divine Food and Fiery Covenants: The Significance of Ash in Ancient Maya Religion -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAsh is an important and yet understudied aspect of ritual deposition in the archaeological record of North America. Ash has been found in a wide variety of contexts across many regions and often it is associated with rare or unusual objects or in contexts that suggest its use in the transition or transformation of houses and ritual features. Drawn from across the U.S. and Mesoamerica, the chapters in this volume explore the use, meanings, and cross-cultural patterns present in the use of ash. and highlight the importance of ash in ritual closure, social memory, and cultural transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAntiquities, Prehistoric. 0aManners and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aancestors.  aancient cultures.  aanthropology.  aantiquities archaeology.  aarchaeological record.  aarchaeology.  acatastrophe.  acaves and caverns.  across cultural patterns.  acultural patterns.  acultural transformation.  aengaging.  afire.  aindigenous studies.  amesoamerica.  anative americans.  anorth america.  apage turner.  aphenomenon.  arealistic.  areligion.  areligious rituals.  aritual deposition.  ascientists.  asocial memory.  asocial science.  aunusual objects.1 aAdams, E. Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, E. Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAdler, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaires, Sarah E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBal